Expect Strong F4Q, Looking for a **r** **r** **u** **r** **e** **d** **u** **n** **t** **F** **Y** **2** **6** **Guide**

We think ZS can beat F4Q billings guide of 25.5% yoy by 2-3%. C2Q SASE results thus far were strong & qoq survey results improved. FY26 cons rev of 20% yoy seems a little high for initial org guide. ZS is likely to shift to ARR (over billings) & we see 19% yoy FY26 org growth as likely (implies flat new bus), although a new CFO may instill extra conservatism. A broadening platform coupled w/ ample SASE runway should sustain strong growth & drive shares higher.

**Checks & C2Q Results So Far.** ZS outperformance vs plan in our survey was +3.5%, up vs our C1Q survey of +2.6%. Anecdotal checks talked to healthy C2Q ZS performance and plenty of remaining runway for 20%+ revenue growth in ZIA/ZPA the next couple of years. FTNT and CHKP, this quarter,called out SASE as having good traction and being a key growth driver. PANW also saw strong enterprise SASE ARR growth of 35% yoy this Q, vs 36% in F3Q, which bodes well for ZS as well.

**F4Q Billings.** F4Q billings expectations of $1.143B (+25.5% yoy) call for flat yoy growth in new business vs 11% yoy in F3Q, but on an 14 pt tougher comp (not accounting for booked but not billed), which looks achievable. Management noted that unscheduled billings grew 28% yoy in F3Q.We expect outperformance of 2-3% on billings in F4Q vs the average of 2.8% over the past 4 Qs.This is supported by strong checks and a seasonally strong F4Q for ZS.

**FY26 Rev Expectations.** Cons FY26 revenue expectations are for 20% yoy growth to $3.2B. This compares to ARR growth of 23% yoy in F3Q and expectations for approx 20% yoy overall ARR growth in FY25, making it feel a touch high for what we perceive will be an eventual conservative opening guide (new CFO). If we assume that ZS beats revenue expectations by 2% in F4Q (in line with the average over the past 2 quarters) then cons implied FY26 rev growth would still be 19.8% yoy. We expect an opening rev guide to be overly prudent and expect an organic revenue guide modestly below cons (which we believe is well understood).

**Focus Shifting to ARR.** ZS reached ARR of $2.9B in F3Q, growing 23% yoy in-line with F2Q. ARR is expected to grow 20%+ in F4Q which may make it tough to provide an opening FY26 guidance in-line or above prior conservative growth expectations of 20% yoy in FY26. We model a mildly more conservative 18% yoy yoy growth, which we feel is appropriate given we expect a prudent opening guide, especially with a new CFO. Note that our current forecasts exclude any benefit from Red Canary. We believe that investor expectations are for approx 19% yoy of organic ARR growth guide which implies approx flat growth in yoy new ARR if we assume that ZS grows ARR 23% yoy in F4Q.
See checks and survey work embedded in the note.

**Annick Baumann * | Equity Associate**

Zscaler's highly scalable software/internet- based architecture makes the company particularly well positioned to disrupt and potentially transform multiple IT network and security markets over time. We view the company as among the best- placed for the future development of a software- driven consolidated IT Security market in a more distributed and cloud- based world. ZS is in the early stages of monetizing this opportunity (we estimate \(\) 60B\(TAM in CY23), which justifies a premium valuation.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

Continued progress towards FY25 guidance and longer- term goals Continued strong subscription growth at \(25\% +\) FCF margin continues to trend upwards of \(20\%\) Price target \(\) 350\(target multiple: 19x EV/ CY25E revenue.\)

ZS outperforms its revenue guidance due to strong adoption of cloud- based network solutions Subscription growth above \(30\% +\) FCF margin far succeeds \(20\%\) Price target \(\) 403\(target multiple: 22x EV/ CY25E revenue.\)

Markets take longer to 'digest' past security purchases than anticipated Subscription growth considerably below \(20\%\) A deterioration in FCF margin to below \(20\%\) Price target \(\) 260\(target multiple: 14x EV/ CY25E revenue.\)

Top Material Issues: (1) Energy Management. We believe cloud- based software services will continue to grow, leading to demand for datacenters. Datacenters consume both energy and water, meaning this should be an area of focus for software companies looking to reduce their CO2 emissions. (2) Employee Engagement, Diversity & Inclusion. We see company culture as important in a labor market that continues to be defined by a skills shortage. Furthermore, given the known underrepresentation of women and minority groups in the software industry today, a focus on building a diverse workforce is key.
Company Target: Goal to retain net zero emissions by 2025.

Questions for Mgmt: (1) How does your cloud- based approach impact customers' environmental footprint vs alternative solutions? (2) What are some of the definitive actions you are taking to diversify your workforce, and you have any DEI initiatives?
Software ESG Integration Refresh
Continued trend in having a distributed workforce i.e. WFA Migration to the cloud Increased adoption of cloud products Continued product innovation and growth of newer solutions

Valuation. Our \(\) 350\(PT implies 15x CY26E reverse\) \Delta \(\) 1.2x\(which we believe is deserved due to a very large & growing\) \Delta \(\) 1.2x\(and enterprise exposure, though this multiple certainly raises the risk profile. This compares to\) \Delta \(\) 28x\(, PANW's 11x, DDOG's 12x and SNOW's 15x.\) \Delta \(\)

- SASE Has Plenty of Runway Left. The expert saw firewall vendors PANW/FTNT/CHKP performing quite well in C2Q; while SASE also showed strength. He noted that he does not expect a downturn for firewall vendors in 2H. ZS was noted as the leader in SASE with healthy C2Q performance and plenty of remaining runway for \(20\% +\) growth the next couple years.- Network Security Show Healthy Performance. CHKP/PANW/FTNT performed slightly above plan. Our expert noted that ZS performed above plan, with ZTNA performing well, and with ZFlex pricing being in effect during C2Q. He also observed ZS sales turnover stabilize.
See full note and expert details here.

Shifting to ARR. Billings may take a similar shape in FY26 as FY25 (back half loaded given booked but not billed phenomenon but less pronounced due to FY25 comps). We therefore expect management will pivot to talking exclusively about ARR. This shift will be beneficial in our view, removing a lot of lumpiness and confusion in the business. However, we highlight that ZS defines ARR as exit rate ARR, making it more difficult to model ARR to ensuing quarter revenue.

Macro Dynamics. In F3Q, ZS noted that customers remain cautious and that the ability to show ROI remains important. Overall, macro commentary indicated a similar environment qoq which at the time contrasted other off Q names who noted a difficult April. Overall, vendors that reported C2Q results so far have seen stability in macro qoq.

New CFO. ZS has appointed Kevin Rubin as its new CFO. Mr Rubin was previously the CFO of BetterUp, Alteryx and MSC Software among others. While it's still early we believe Mr Rubin will continue to be focused on growth, with a balanced approach to profitability. Former CFO Remo Canessa will remain at ZS in an advisory capacity until the end of FY25, after which he will retire.

Red Canary Acquisition. On Aug 4, ZS closed the acquisition of Red Canary for \(\) 675M\(in cash, plus equity for employees. Red Canary was founded in 2014 and is a Managed Detection and Response (MDR) company. Red Canary previously reported having surpassed\) \ \(140M\) in ARR in January 2025 vs \(\) 100M\(in April 2023. We believe that current growth is high teens and we remain optimistic that ZS can re- accelerate the growth of Red Canary. ZS expects to eventually retain approx\) \ \(70M\) of ARR from Red Canary, but insisted that it acquired the asset mainly for the talent and technology (we suspect it may maintain more than\) \ \(70M\) . We expect this business to accelerate ZS' capabilities in the security operations space which was already boosted by the previous acquisition of Avalor and hire of Adam Geller to run product (Adam was previously the CEO of Exabeam, a SIEM company). This combination of companies, technology and talent with ZS' ample threat data makes it feasible for ZS to meaningfully penetrate the SIEM market.

Federal Momentum. ZS still sees its penetration within federal as relatively low and even with seat pressure there is room for expansion in management's view. That said, it has mid single digit of billings exposure to Fed (see Chart 2) and if there is near- term uncertainty that could certainly weigh on upside. While management did not embed an outsized impact from federal in F2H, fed headwinds would likely impact F1Q26 guidance given the timing of the Fed's year- end. PANW saw an uptick in its F4Q Public sector bookings growth rates and appeared less cautious about the Fed spending environment which bodes well for ZS.

Sales Re- Alignment. In F3Q, it was evident that management continues to be hyper focused on removing friction from the sales process via its Z- Flex motion. Large enterprises will be the first ones to have access to ZS' Z- Flex, its new flexible consumption model. ZS is focused on broadening the adoption of its platform via Z- Flex, although there is the chance that this pressures margins in the near- term.

Profitability Progress. FY25 non- GAAP op margin guide implies 120 bps of leverage yoy (vs 6pts in FY24), while FCF margin guide was raised to 25.5- 26% (vs 24.5- 25% prev), in F3Q, and compares to 27% in FY24. Datacenter CAPEX of 11% of revenue in F3Q is above 3% in F1H, and is expected to be 9% in FY25 (prev expectations were closer to 10%), which will continue to constrain FCF margin. ZS did raise FY25 non- GAAP op margin guide by 20bps and we would expect ZS to beat F4Q guidance, of 21.7% at the midpoint, as well (guidance implies little to no leverage vs F3Q margin). That said, management remains much more focused on growth, and we expected more muted margin upside given the investments in a ramping salesforce.

FY26 Profitability. FY26 non GAAP op margin expectations are for 22.4% in FY26, up from the approx 22% guide for FY25, which we see as a reasonable starting point for a guide (although M&A could weigh). FY26 FCF expectations are for 27.9% margin vs FY25 guidance of 25.5- 26.0% and 27% seen in FY24. We would expect ZS to start with a slightly more conservative FCF guide in FY26 roughly in- line with FY25 reported numbers especially as it attempts to integrate Red Canary and it takes time to optimize costs.

Firewall Refresh Opportunity. PANW, FTNT and CHKP saw good traction for product in C2Q. We think this indicates enterprise customer appetite to buy/upgrade product, which may be an opportunity for ZS to displace. ZS sees the displacement opportunity mainly within its existing client base as these customers have already shown interest in reducing the number of firewalls.

Zscaler was founded in 2007 by its current CEO Jay Chaudhry and has approximately 5,000 employees today. Zscaler's main product ZIA offers both outbound and inbound web and network protection via the company's edge servers, which serve as proxies that direct and filter traffic between internal users and external untrusted sources. Its ZPA product creates a private portal that enables trusted users to access a company's internal network resources and data, replacing traditional VPN functionalities. Other key Zscaler products include, ZS for Workloads its cloud workload and data security solution and ZDX a multi- tenant cloud- based monitoring platform for an organization's users. Zscaler's Zero Trust Exchange is distributed across more than 150 data centers worldwide.
Our \(\) 350\(price target is based on a DCF and implies 19x EV/CY25E revenue. Downside risks include markets taking longer to' digest' past security purchases than anticipated.
